## ITTTT: Other Operators in Command Injection

IF â†’ You have confirmed command injection (e.g. output reflects command execution)  
THEN â†’ Test with `; whoami`, `&& whoami`, `|| whoami`

---

IF â†’ You want the **second command only if the first works**  
THEN â†’ Use `&&`  
Example: `127.0.0.1 && id`

---

IF â†’ You want the **second command only if the first fails**  
THEN â†’ Use `||`  
Example: `|| whoami`

---

IF â†’ You want **both commands to run regardless**  
THEN â†’ Use `;`  
Example: `127.0.0.1; id`

---

IF â†’ Your injection is blocked by JavaScript/frontend regex  
THEN â†’ Use Burp, intercept request, encode payload (`CTRL+U`), send in Repeater.

---

IF â†’ Youâ€™re testing in a **blind situation (no output)**  
THEN â†’ Use `; sleep 5`, time-based, or redirect output to file.

ğŸ§  Patterns + Hints
ğŸ” Always test commands locally first before injecting â€” confirms syntax

ğŸ§ª Rotate ops: Try ;, then &&, then || â€” see what leaks what.

ğŸ§¨ || is OP as hell when you break the first command on purpose.

ğŸ¯ ping -c 1 || whoami = fail ping â†’ execute your payload.

ğŸ“ Some apps log only failed commands, so chaining might stealth better with &&.

ğŸ’» Windows CMD doesnâ€™t like ; â€” try &, &&, or PowerShell format

ğŸ¤« Want clean output? Use || whoami without extra stuff like ping.

